author: Rick Nivens
notes: All \p\" in these data are allophones of the voiceless bilabial fricative phoneme /ɸ/

id: All \"y\" in these data represent IPA [j] (palatal approximant).
The \"ê\" is between [ɪ] and [e]; similarly the [ô] is between [ʊ] and [o]. These two phonemes are innovations due to assimilation to nearby high vowels (which were then lost).
The \"ɛ\" here is phonetically between [e] and [ɛ]
Acute accent here represents stress on final syllable of root."
author: Austronesian, Malayo-Polynesian, Central-Eastern, Central Malayo-Polynesian, Aru
